en (well, energy density actually) and how the energy they give off is released.<br>
<br>
The easiest reaction to ignite is Deuterium-Tritium fusion.  The disadvantage is that the large majority of the energy is given off in the form of a 14Mev neutron.  That sucker will basically penetrate mostly anything.  D-D fusion is second easiest to ignite, and also gives off many hot neutrons.<br>
<br>
D-He3 fusion is third easiest to ignite, but gives off the bulk of its energy in the form of a proton.  MUCH easier to shield against even a high energy proton.  D-He3 is not perfectly aneitronic, however.  Since D-D is an easier reaction to light, some fraction of the D fuses with itself rather than the Helium3, and thus produces those nasty neutrons.  This can be largely mitigated by running the reaction very helium3 rich, to minimize that side reaction.<br>
<br>
The lowest energy perfectly aneutronic fusion reaction involves Boron12.  It is HARD to light, so it's pretty much off the chart for now.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=captainbeowulf>CaptainBeowulf</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 13<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/17/03 12:08 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=133.topic&index=123>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Here is a plan for a nuclear thermal rocket space launch</span><hr size=1> What fusion systems do people think we are likely to see first?  Will we get D-D fusion plants on earth first, antimatter catalyzed microfission/fusion explosion rockets in space, and then D-He3 fusion in space and perhaps back on earth... or will something else come into play? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nebobgrenville>nebobgrenville</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://my.oregonstate.edu/courses/1/NE_114_X001_F2002/uploads/homepage/_1060577_1/triga.jpg" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 237<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/17/03 2:17 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=133.topic&index=124>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Here is a plan for a nuclear thermal rocket space launch</span><hr size=1> The first will be D-T fusion tested here on Earth in all likelyhood. It is the easiest to do and the process being tested in most current test devices. As D can bew naturaly harvested from simple seawater it is likely that the first application of largescale electrical generation will involve the D-D process. Tritium is primarily produced in reactors, so is expencive to procure. <p>&quot;If,&quot; he wispered, &quot;if we could only pick that lock....&quot; - , THE WORLD SET FREE</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=whitestar60>whitestar60</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 140<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/17/03 3:59 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=133.topic&index=125>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Here is a plan for a nuclear thermal rocket space launch</span><hr size=1> What is the energy produced by boron fusion? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nebobgrenville>nebobgrenville</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://my.oregonstate.edu/courses/1/NE_114_X001_F2002/uploads/homepage/_1060577_1/triga.jpg" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 239<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/17/03 4:27 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=133.topic&index=126>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Here is a plan for a nuclear thermal rocket space launch</span><hr size=1> A source I found listed that a total of 8.7 MeV is released in the form of kenetic energy in alpha particles. Unlike energy in neutrons or photons, all the energy in the alphas can be recovered. The benifits of no neutron radiation and a plentiful fuel stock (we have a lot of boron) make it the 'holy grail' of fusion power. <p>&quot;If,&quot; he wispered, &quot;if we could only pick that lock....&quot; - , THE WORLD SET FREE</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=whitestar60>whitestar60</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 141<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/18/03 6:52 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=133.topic&index=127>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Here is a plan for a nuclear thermal rocket space launch</span><hr size=1> [qoute]A source I found listed that a total of 8.7 MeV is released in the form of kenetic energy in alpha particles. Unlike energy in neutrons or photons, all the energy in the alphas can be recovered. [/qoute]<br>
